# How to Build automatically when pushed on github

Step 1: Check Jenkins build trigger
    Go to your job â†’ Configure â†’ Build Triggers.
    Make sure you ticked:
        GitHub hook trigger for GITScm polling.

Step 2: Confirm webhook in GitHub
    Repo â†’ Settings â†’ Webhooks.
    Make sure the URL is:
        http://<publicly-accessible-jenkins>/github-webhook/

    In Recent Deliveries, check if GitHub says âœ… â€œ200 OKâ€ or âŒ â€œfailedâ€.
    (Iâ€™m guessing yours will show failed because 10.0.2.15 isnâ€™t public).

Step 3: Make Jenkins reachable from GitHub

You have two options:

ğŸ”¹ Option A: Quick local test (without internet)
Instead of using webhook, use Poll SCM:

i.  In Jenkins job â†’ Configure â†’ Build Triggers â†’ Poll SCM.
ii. Enter schedule:
                    * * * * *
            (This means Jenkins checks every 1 minute for GitHub changes).

iii. Save.
iv.  Now, whenever you push a commit to GitHub â†’ Jenkins will detect it within 1 min and build.

        âš¡ Works without exposing your Jenkins to GitHub. (Good for your VM test!)


ğŸ”¹ Option B: Real Webhook with GitHub

If you want instant builds from GitHub webhook:

i. Install ngrok inside your VM or host machine.
        ngrok http 8080

ii. It will give a public URL like:
        https://random123.ngrok.io

iii. Use this in GitHub webhook:
        https://random123.ngrok.io/github-webhook/

